  "doc_id": "17637",
  "text": "3D structure and alternative representations. For a long time, one of the most common representations for molecular structures has been a fingerprint, a fixed-length vector indicating the presence or absence of a chemical environment [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Fingerprints are not typically invertible but can be used for fast screening by similarity to available in-house compounds. Kadurin et al. [CITATION_3] implemented VAE and AAE models based on Molecular Access System (MACCS) fingerprints to screen for novel compounds with the desired effect. Polykovskiy et al. [CITATION_4] proposed a generative model for creating molecular structures for a given fingerprint, training a simple generator on fingerprints and then transforming them into SMILES with a separate model. However, fingerprints often lack biological relevance and do not fit into the process of designing novel compounds.",
